article.description: Lauren Jackson scored 27 points to help the Storm push their winning streak to six games with a 74-61 victory over the Silver Stars on Saturday night.
article.headline: Jackson plays in 100th WNBA game
article.linkText: Jackson, Storm outstrip Silver Spurs in rout
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Lauren Jackson and the streaking Seattle
Storm overpowered the lowly San Antonio Silver Stars.

The Australian star, in the headlines recently after posing nude
for an Australian magazine, scored 27 points to help the Storm
extend their winning streak to six games with a 74-61 victory
Saturday night.

She was 10-of-15 from the field, hitting both of her 3-point
attempts, and went 5-of-6 from the line in her 100th WNBA game.

"She was pretty impressive to say the least," Storm coach Anne
Donovan said. "We knew headed in that one-on-one she was going to
be tough to stop. She did a great job of taking advantage of that
matchup early in the game."

Betty Lennox added 16 and nine rebounds for the league-leading
Storm (8-2), while Kamila Vodichkova scored 10 points, including
the 1,000th of her career. Sue Bird had nine points and a season-
high nine assists, with only one turnover.

The Storm end a three-game road trip that included a 69-63
victory over the Houston Comets on Friday night.

"We just have so many threats offensively on this team,"
Donovan said. "We had three people in double figures tonight. With
as many threats as we have on the floor at one time, we should be
able to do that almost every night."

San Antonio has lost a franchise-record eight straight games.

"It's tough losing," Silver Stars center Margo Dydek said.
"For me, this is the first time in this league to lose eight
games. It's frustrating, but we'll get over it."

LaToya Thomas had 16 points for the Silver Stars, a WNBA-worst
3-9. Marie Ferdinand added 12 points, and Adrienne Goodson had 11.

"We need to play together," Thomas said. "It's our first time
to play together as a team, but it will come. It's going to take
time. We have new coaches and new players.
